codex
**Findings**
1. `parse_rfc3339_epoch` is still not strict RFC3339, so the pass-2 parser blocker is not fully closed. The new code now rejects the specific cases you called out: impossible dates, out-of-range zone offsets, and bad fractional-second suffixes. But it still accepts malformed non-canonical shapes because it only splits and numeric-parses components, without enforcing fixed widths for year/month/day/time/offset fields. By inspection, forms like `2026-6-1T7:3:9Z`, `2026-06-01T07:23:39+5:00`, and `12026-06-01T07:23:39Z` would pass the current checks at [perf-regression-check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:132), [perf-regression-check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:165), and [perf-regression-check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:187), then be treated as valid history rows by [perf-regression-check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:224). That contradicts the documented “strict RFC3339” contract in [perf-regression-detection.md](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/dev/design/perf-regression-detection.md:124). The unit tests do cover the newly added pass-2 cases, but they do not cover these remaining lenient paths: [perf-regression-check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:516) and [perf-regression-check.rs](/tmp/fdb-PR-7-20260601T215338Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-cli/src/bin/perf-regression-check.rs:529).

The rest of the slice looked aligned on static re-scan: latest-vs-prior windowing/off-by-one, exit-code mapping, append-only read-only behavior, `(ac_id, n)` grouping, and unknown-field tolerance for `note` all read correctly in the diff. I could not re-run `cargo test`, `clippy`, or `actionlint` in this harness because the sandbox is read-only and denied writes even under `/tmp`, so this pass is based on code/diff inspection rather than live execution.

